Intergenerational justice concerns obligations present generations owe to future generations, especially under conditions of uncertainty and irreversibility. The field addresses fundamental questions: Can we have duties to non-existent people? What do we owe those whose preferences remain unknown? How should we balance present needs against future welfare when our decisions have permanent consequences?

Three major debates structure this domain. First, the non-identity problem (Parfit) questions whether we can harm future people when our choices determine who exists. Second, theories of obligation divide between reciprocity-based accounts (Gosseries), sufficientarian approaches (Timmer), and relational egalitarian frameworks (Bengtson, Lippert-Rasmussen). Third, the role of uncertainty creates tensions between optimization, satisficing, and option-preservation strategies.

Epistemic justice literature (Fricker 2007, Medina 2013) traditionally addresses testimonial and hermeneutical injustices against marginalized groups. Recent work extends these concepts to planning and policy contexts (Anderson 2012, Byskov & Hyams 2023), revealing how decision-making frameworks can systematically exclude certain forms of knowledge or impose epistemic harms on future generations. The connection between epistemic constraints and intergenerational obligations remains underexplored, creating an opening for arguments that epistemic humility about future preferences demands preserving options rather than optimizing based on present assumptions.

