This domain directly addresses the core tension in the research project: urban planning decisions bind future generations whose preferences are unknown, creating both epistemic constraints (we cannot know what they will value) and irreversibility (urban form persists across generations). The literature provides frameworks for thinking about obligations under uncertainty, the moral significance of option preservation, and how epistemic duties to future knowers might constrain present decision-making authority.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
While intergenerational justice literature addresses uncertainty about future welfare, it rarely engages systematically with epistemic justice frameworks. Conversely, epistemic justice literature focuses primarily on contemporaneous relationships, not duties to future knowers. The intersection—epistemic duties to future generations as a constraint on present planning authority—remains largely untheorized.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Look for connections between: (1) Gosseries and Fricker on how reciprocity/credibility structures might extend intergenerationally; (2) Zwarthoed and Medina on how option preservation relates to epistemic capacity-building; (3) Doorn 2025 and Anderson 2012 on institutional design for epistemic justice under uncertainty. The sufficientarian literature (Timmer, Benbaji) may provide resources for thinking about threshold duties distinct from optimization.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Contractualism (Rawls, Gosseries): 5 papers - Obligations grounded in hypothetical agreement or reciprocity across generations
- Sufficientarianism (Timmer, Benbaji): 3 papers - Threshold-based duties distinct from maximization or equality
- Epistemic Justice (Fricker, Medina, Anderson): 5 papers - Duties to recognize diverse knowers and avoid testimonial/hermeneutical harms
- Option Preservation (Zwarthoed, Doorn): 2 papers - Obligations to maintain choice-sets rather than optimize
- Relational Egalitarianism (Bengtson, Lippert-Rasmussen, Chan): 3 papers - Justice as equal social relations extended intergenerationally
====================================================================
}

